==Championship==
{{main|2014–15 Football League Championship}}
The fixtures for the [[2014–15 Football League Championship]] season were released on 18 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/championship/fixtures |title=Championship Fixtures|publisher=[[BBC Sport]] |date=2014-06-18 |accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref>

===August===
Bolton began their third consecutive season in the second tier away at [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on 9 August. Wanderers conceded three goals without reply; [[Troy Deeney]], [[Matěj Vydra]] and [[Fernando Forestieri]] scoring the goals for the Hornets. Their first league fixture at the newly renamed Macron Stadium was against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] a week later. All four goals of the 2-2 draw came in the first half; [[Joe Mason (footballer, born 1991)|Joe Mason]] first headed in a [[Jay Spearing]] free-kick before [[Britt Assombalonga]] equalised for Forest. [[David Wheater]] put Bolton back in front but [[Captain (association football)|captain]] Jay Spearing brought down Assombalonga in the box, who picked himself up to draw Forest level again. Against [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]], [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] put Bolton in front with a penalty in the 27th minute after being brought down by [[Seb Hines]]. [[David Wheater]] was then adjudged to have handled in the box just before half-time - leading to [[Grant Leadbitter]] equalising for Boro, again from the spot. [[Kike (footballer, born November 1989)|Kike]] scored a late winner to give Middlesbrough their first win away at Bolton since 1987. Away to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton]] and [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]], Bolton lost 2-1 and 1-0, respectively, to leave them winless after five games. Bolton took the lead against Brighton, [[Matt Mills]] opening the scoring but goals from [[Craig Mackail-Smith]] and [[João Carlos Teixeira|João Teixeira]] gave Brighton the points. Former Bolton loanee [[Stephen Warnock]] scored the only goal for Leeds, consigning them to defeat once again. [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] was named player of the month for August, scoring two goals from the penalty spot.<ref>http://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/article/craig-davies-wins-clubs-player-of-the-month-award-for-august-5.9.14-1899344.aspx</ref>

===September===
Bolton started September against [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], the result being a goalless draw. This brought an end to their three match losing streak but meant they still hadn't won a league game this season, extending their winless start to the season to six games. Bolton ended their next game on the right side of a five-goal thriller. [[Anthony Wordsworth]] put [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham]] in front in the first half but [[Joe Mason (footballer, born 1991)|Joe Mason]] scored two to bring Bolton ahead with ten minutes remaining on the clock. Two minutes later, [[Jordan Bowery]] equalised for the Millers but Mason scored his first career hat-trick and the club's first since [[Fredi Bobic]] put in three against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in 2002, to hand Bolton their first win of the new season. They couldn't follow this up with a second, however, and lost by a solitary goal at [[Molineux Stadium|Molineux]] against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolves]]; [[Nouha Dicko]] scoring the goal for the hosts. Against [[Steve McLaren|Steve McLaren's]] [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]], Bolton conceded a goal either side of half-time to send them back into the relegation zone. The loss sparked mass protests from the crowd during the game, with fans chanting for both manager [[Dougie Freedman]] and chairman [[Phil Gartside]] to leave their posts.<ref>{{cite web|title=FULL TIME: Wanderers 0 Derby County 2|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/wanderers/bolton_wanderers/11500562.FULL_TIME__Wanderers_0_Derby_County_2/?ref=mac|website=www.theboltonnews.co.uk|publisher=The Bolton News|accessdate=28 September 2014}}</ref>

===October===
A few days later, on the first of the month, Bolton conceded four goals without reply as they fell to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] at [[Craven Cottage]], one of two teams that were below them in the table.

Following the defeat to Fulham, manager [[Dougie Freedman]] was relieved of his duties. Initially, the club indicated that Freedman would remain in his position for the match against [[A.F.C. Bournemouth|Bournemouth]] at the weekend, as they confirmed he would be taking his weekly press conference on Friday 3 October.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bolton Wanderers confirm Dougie Freedman to stay on as manager for Bournemouth game|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/wanderers/bolton_wanderers/11511468.Wanderers_confirm_Freedman_to_stay_on_as_manager_for_Bournemouth_game/?ref=mac|website=www.theboltonnews.co.uk|publisher=The Bolton News|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> However, the following day a statement was released explaining that Freedman had left the club 'by mutual consent'.<ref>{{cite web|title=Club statement: Dougie Freedman leaves Bolton Wanderers|url=http://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/article/club-statement-dougie-freedman-leaves-bolton-wanderers-3.10.14-1986207.aspx|website=www.bwfc.co.uk|publisher=Bolton Wanderers F.C.|accessdate=3 October 2014}}</ref> Player-coach [[Andrew Hughes (footballer, born 1978)|Andy Hughes]] and goalkeeping coach Lee Turner were confirmed as caretaker managers for the game against the Cherries by the club's website the following day.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lee Turner and Andy Hughes in charge for Bournemouth visit|url=http://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/article/lee-turner-and-andy-hughes-in-charge-for-bournemouth-visit-4.10.14-1987940.aspx|website=www.bwfc.co.uk|publisher=Bolton Wanderers F.C.|accessdate=7 October 2014}}</ref>

Against Bournemouth, Cherries striker [[Yann Kermorgant]] was sent off in the 36th minute. Despite this, Bournemouth won 2-1 with [[Callum Wilson (English footballer)|Callum Wilson]] scoring both their goals either side of a [[Jay Spearing]] equaliser in the 52nd minute.

Nine days later, during the international break, former [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]] manager [[Neil Lennon]] was handed the job of moving Bolton off the bottom of the table.<ref name="Neil Lennon appointed Bolton Wanderers manager">{{cite web|title=Neil Lennon appointed Bolton Wanderers manager|url=http://www.bwfc.co.uk/news/article/neil-lennon-appointed-bolton-wanderers-manager-12.10.14-2011942.aspx|website=www.bwfc.co.uk|publisher=Bolton Wanderers F.C.|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> The former [[Northern Ireland national football team|Northern Ireland]] international was confirmed as the Trotters' new manager "following a process of first and second interviews with a shortlist of initial candidates".<ref name="Neil Lennon appointed Bolton Wanderers manager"/>

Lennon's first game came against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] at [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St. Andrew's]], against whom he had made his [[Football League]] debut as a player for [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]. [[Matt Mills]] headed in from a corner to give Bolton a lead they managed to hang on to despite [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] missing a penalty while striker [[Lee Novak]] was in goal, having replaced the sent off [[Darren Randolph]]. Following this, Neil Lennon was sent to the stands as he had left his technical area too many times throughout the match. This was Bolton's second win of the season, and lifted them off the bottom of the table, to be replaced by [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. At [[The Valley (London)|The Valley]], [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton]] scored either side of half-time to go 2-0 up, before [[Dean Moxey]] scored his first for the club to make the score 2-1 just a few minutes later, but the team couldn't score an equaliser, giving Lennon his first taste of defeat as Bolton manager. At home for the first time, [[Neil Danns]] and [[Mark Davies (footballer)|Mark Davies]] scored while [[Jon Toral]] did so for [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]]. Ensuring the win, [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] scored with Brentford's 'keeper up the pitch to make it 3-1. With 10% more possession but 10 fewer shots, Bolton fell to [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] at [[Carrow Road]] in front of the [[British Sky Broadcasting|Sky]] cameras. [[Cameron Jerome]] scored a brace while [[Lee Chung-yong]] scored his first of the season with just four minutes remaining.

===November===
Neil Lennon clinched his second straight home win against [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], scoring three with no reply against the Bluebirds. [[Liam Feeney]] slid to connect with [[Lee Chung-yong|Lee Chung-yong's]] arrowed cross from the right for his first of the season just nine minutes in before doubling his tally on 36 minutes when [[Darren Pratley]] found him with a cross to the back post. [[Matt Mills]] sealed the win with 14 minutes remaining to become Bolton's joint-top scorer in all competitions alongside [[Joe Mason (footballer, born 1991)|Joe Mason]]. Against local rivals [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]], Bolton scored three goals for the third home game in a row. [[Max Clayton]] scored his first for the club after latching on to [[Lee Chung-yong|Lee Chung-yong's]] through ball before [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] headed in from [[Liam Feeney|Liam Feeney's]] looped cross to make it two. Six minutes later, Chung-yong added to his earlier assist with a goal from the penalty spot; [[Leon Barnett]] having been adjudged to have brought down [[Matt Mills]] in the box. [[Callum McManaman]] volleyed in a consolation but the win brought Bolton out of the relegation zone going into the international break. Their first match following this saw them come up against [[Blackpool F.C.|Blackpool]]. Blackpool took the lead through [[Jacob Murphy]], before [[Lee Chung-yong]] scored for the second consecutive game to get Bolton a point. Bolton finished the month with a 1-0 home win against [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], [[Craig Davies (footballer)|Craig Davies]] scoring late into the first half to get Bolton the three points.

===December===
Bolton started December with consecutive goalless draws, the first against [[Reading F.C.|Reading]] at the [[Madejski Stadium]], followed by a stalemate against [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] at the [[Macron Stadium]]. [[Eiður Guðjohnsen]] made his second début in the match, 14 years after his last appearance against the same opponents, in May 2000. Bolton would make it three clean sheets in a row the following week, defeating [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] at [[The Den]] from a [[Darren Pratley]] goal in the second half. On [[Boxing Day]] Bolton faced local rivals [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] at the [[Macron Stadium|Macron]], playing in front of a home crowd of over 20,000 for the first time in nearly three years. [[Joshua King (footballer)|Josh King]] scored for Blackburn, before 37-year-old [[Emile Heskey]] scored on his debut after coming off the bench, the assist coming from fellow 37-year-old [[Eiður Guðjohnsen]]. [[Darren Pratley]] scored his second goal in as many games four minutes later, giving Bolton the bragging rights over their rivals. Two days later they played their last game of 2014, their eight match unbeaten run coming to an end as they lost 2-1 to [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]. Bolton took the lead in the 41st minute with [[Darren Pratley]] scoring for the third consecutive match followed two minutes later by an equaliser from former Bolton player [[Jacob Butterfield]]. [[Nahki Wells]] scored with five minutes remaining seeing Bolton lose their last match of 2014.

===January===
Following a break for the [[FA Cup]] Bolton's first league game of 2015 came at home against [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]]. [[Rudolph Austin]] scored a penalty for Leeds in the third minute but just after half time, Bolton got a penalty of their own. [[Eiður Guðjohnsen]] stepped up and scored the equaliser and earning a point for Bolton, it being his first Bolton goal since resigning for the club the previous month, his last goal for Bolton before that coming 15 years earlier May 2000. The week later, Bolton faced [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]], getting back to winning ways as they won 2-1 at [[Hillsborough Stadium|Hillsborough]], their third consecutive away win over Wednesday. [[Liam Feeney]] opened the scoring in the second minute with [[Darren Pratley]] adding a second twenty minutes later. [[Chris Maguire]] pulled one back from the penalty spot three minutes later but Bolton held on to claim their first league win of 2015. After the 4th round of the FA Cup, Bolton went to [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]] and were 4-0 down after fifty seven minutes, [[Ben Pringle]], [[Conor Sammon]] and [[Paul Green (footballer, born 1983)|Paul Green]] scoring in the first half, before [[Matt Derbyshire]] added a fourth. Bolton pulled two back by scoring twice in two minutes through [[Liam Trotter]] and [[Matt Mills]] but it wasn't enough as Rotherham ran out 4-2 winners. Bolton finished January at home against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]]. [[Nouha Dicko]] scored in the third minute to give Wolves the lead but 20 minutes later, [[Zach Clough]], on his league début, scored twice within two minutes - his third goal for the club in only his second appearance - to give Bolton the lead. Deep into injury time though [[James Henry (footballer, born 1989)|James Henry]] equalised with a long distance shot, earning his side a share of the spoils.

For the second season in a row, the club's final fixture of the season will be at home to [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on 2 May 2015.

