== Transfers ==

=== Summer ===
Bolton's first move of the transfer window was confirmed on 28 April 2014, with loanee [[Neil Danns]] signing a pre-contract which would see him move to the club on a one-year deal once his existing contract with [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] expired on 30 June.

On 5 May 2014, it was announced that four senior players would not have their contracts renewed. Club captain [[Zat Knight]], [[Chris Eagles]], [[Tyrone Mears]] and Jay Lynch were all released. On the same day the club confirmed that academy players Sam Bailey, Saul Hamer, Jordan Hendrie, James Kelly, Elliot Newby and Guillermo Torres would not have their contracts extended.

On 12 May, Bolton confirmed that another loanee from the previous season would be joining the club following the expiring of his current contract in the summer. Following Neil Danns' example, [[Liam Trotter]] would join the club on 1 July, signing a three-year deal, leaving [[Millwall F.C.|Millwall]] after four years of service. On 19 May, Bolton confirmed that [[Liam Feeney]], another ex-loanee, would be following Trotter from Millwall after signing a two-year deal, having been at Millwall for three years. On 21 May, Bolton signed their fourth former loanee in a row, with [[Andy Robinson (footballer born 1992)|Andy Robinson]] of [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] joining on a one-year deal. However, on 19 July the club confirmed the player had left as he had failed to settle in the area. Bolton's fifth signing of the summer was confirmed as former [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham]] defender [[Dorian Dervite]], who signed a three-year deal, joining from [[Charlton Athletic F.C.|Charlton Athletic]]. Bolton continued their summer signing spree by announcing on 12 June that [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] youth goalkeeper Ross Fitzsimons would officially become a Trotter on 1 July, with the 'keeper signing a two-year contract.

On 1 July, as well as confirming the arrivals of the six previously announced signings, Bolton revealed that [[André Moritz]] and [[Arran Lee-Barrett]] would leave the club following the expiration of their contracts. Both had been discussing the option of a contract extension.<ref name="Bolton Wanderers: Andre Moritz and Arran Lee-Barrett leave club"/>

The following day, on 2 July, Bolton announced the signing of [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] left-back [[Dean Moxey]], with whom Freedman had previously worked during his time with the Eagles. Two days later, striker [[Marvin Sordell]] left Bolton to join near neighbours [[Burnley F.C.|Burnley]] in the [[Premier League]], rejoining his former manager at [[Watford F.C.|Watford]], [[Sean Dyche]]. Defender [[Alex Baptiste]], recently arrested on suspicion of [[Assault occasioning actual bodily harm|actual bodily harm]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Miranda Newey|title=Bolton Wanderers star Alex Baptiste arrested after alleged attack on man who touched his wife's bottom|url=http://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/sport/wanderers/wanderersnews/11327089.Bolton_Wanderers_star_arrested_after_alleged_attack_on_man_who_touched_his_wife_s_bottom/?ref=mac|website=www.theboltonnews.co.uk|publisher=The Bolton News|accessdate=11 July 2014}}</ref> was loaned to [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 11 July.

A fifth former loanee, [[Kevin McNaughton]], joined the club on 16 July, signing on for another loan spell. On 19 July, [[Andy Robinson (footballer born 1992)|Andy Robinson]], who had only joined the club at the beginning of the month, had his contract cancelled with homesickness being cited as the reason.

Shortly after, experienced utility man [[Andrew Hughes (footballer, born 1978)|Andy Hughes]] joined the club as a professional development coach, while also be registered as a member of the playing staff. [[Keith Andrews (footballer)|Keith Andrews]] then joined [[Watford F.C.|Watford]] on loan on 24 July, before Bolton signed young defender Quade Taylor on a free from Crystal Palace and [[Joe Riley (footballer, born 1991)|Joe Riley]] joined [[Oxford United F.C.|Oxford United]] on loan until January, both on 28 July. Young defender [[Cian Bolger]] left the club on 5 August, joining [[Phil Brown (footballer, born 1959)|Phil Brown's]] [[Southend United F.C.|Southend United]].

Former [[Plymouth Argyle F.C.|Plymouth]] man [[Joe Mason (footballer, born 1991)|Joe Mason]] rejoined the club on 11 August, signing on for another loan spell until the end of the [[2014-15 in English football|2014-15 season]] from [[Cardiff City F.C.|Cardiff City]], with whom he had recently agreed a new contract. The first released Bolton player to join a new club was 'keeper Jay Lynch, who joined [[Accrington Stanley F.C.|Accrington Stanley]] on non-contract terms on 8 August, although he later joined [[Salford City F.C.|Salford City]].

Bolton's first signing of the emergency loan window was to loan [[Owen Garvan]] from [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] until December. Two days later [[Conor Wilkinson]] joined [[Football League One|League One]] team [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] on loan for a month. Right-back [[Hayden White (footballer)|Hayden White]] was also sent out on loan, joining [[Carlisle United F.C.|Carlisle United]] for a month. Coming the other way, [[Max Clayton]] joined after compensation was agreed with his former club [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]]. Clayton had trained with Bolton earlier in the summer following his turning down of a contract extension from the Railwaymen. The BBC reported a figure of £300,000 could be given to Crewe. A day later, [[Paddy Kenny]] released by [[Leeds United A.F.C.|Leeds United]] following rumours [[Massimo Cellino]] had dropped him because he considers the 'keeper's birth date to be unlucky.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paddy Kenny 'dropped by Massimo Cellino because of birth date'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/28153659|website=www.bbc.co.uk|publisher=British Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref> The Irishman signed for Bolton on a short-term deal to cover for the absent [[Ádám Bogdán]], who had been injured while in training. The club's third signing in six days, [[Chris Herd]] joined Bolton from [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] until 8 November.

